      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''To Yankee Second Baseman, Throwing Is No Idle Thought'' (front page, June 17):</p>
        <p>The gifted cellist and teacher David Darling once commented in a workshop I was attending, ''Performing music should be an Olympic event.'' Such is the task.</p>
        <p>My heart goes out to Chuck Knoblauch in his current and painfully public struggle. The territory of performance anxiety has been charted for centuries by musicians of all ages, from the child at her first recital to no less than the master pianist Vladimir Horowitz.</p>
        <p>Professional athletes stand to learn much from musicians in this arena, most notably from another gifted teacher, the late Eloise Ristad. Her groundbreaking book, ''A Soprano on Her Head,'' has enabled many great performances in fields of all kinds.</p>
        <p>NARCISSA CAMPION  Brookline, Mass., June 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
